data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` to combine the type check and assertion:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives a clearer failure message (e.g., "Expected type EmailHandler, actual type SmsHandler") instead of a `NullReferenceException` or `InvalidCastException`.

If you're on older MSTest without the generic overload, use:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
```
